```javascript
function minPath(grid, k) {
  const N = grid.length;
  let minVal = Infinity;
  let startPos = null;

  // Find the minimum value in the grid to potentially start the lexicographical minimum path
  for (let r = 0; r < N; r++) {
    for (let c = 0; c < N; c++) {
      if (grid[r][c] < minVal) {
        minVal = grid[r][c];
        startPos = [r, c];
      }
    }
  }

  // A path of length k is lexicographically smallest if the first element is as small as possible,
  // then the second, and so on.
  // Since we want the minimum path, we should always try to move to the neighbor with the 
  // smallest value. However, since we can revisit cells, the absolute minimum path 
  // will always involve moving from the smallest value to its smallest neighbor 
  // and then potentially bouncing back and forth between those two if that's the best we can do.

  // Actually, the lexicographical rule means we want the sequence (v1, v2, v3...) to be minimal.
  // To minimize (v1, v2, ...), we must minimize v1 first.
  // The minimum possible v1 is the minimum value in the entire grid.
  // Let min_val be the minimum value in the grid.
  // Let its neighbors be N(min_val).
  // The best second element v2 must be the minimum value among all neighbors of min_val.
  // Once we reach v2, the best v3 is the minimum value among all neighbors of v2.
  // Since we can revisit, if we are at v2, the best v3 is either v1 (the smallest value in grid)
  // or some other neighbor. But v1 is the smallest possible value in the entire grid.
  // Therefore, if we can move from v2 back to v1, the sequence will be [min_val, min_neighbor, min_val, min_neighbor...].
  // This is because v1 is the smallest possible value for any position in the sequence.

  let currentR = startPos[0];
  let currentC = startPos[1];
  let result = [grid[currentR][currentC]];

  if (k === 1) return result;

  // Find the smallest neighbor of the starting minimum cell
  let minNeighborVal = Infinity;
  let nextR = -1;
  let nextC = -1;
  const dr = [0, 0, 1, -1];
  const dc = [1, -1, 0, 0];

  for (let i = 0; i < 4; i++) {
    let nr = currentR + dr[i];
    let nc = currentC + dc[i];
    if (nr >= 0 && nr < N && nc >= 0 && nc < N) {
      if (grid[nr][nc] < minNeighborVal) {
        minNeighborVal = grid[nr][nc];
        nextR = nr;
        nextC = nc;
      }
    }
  }

  // Now we have the sequence: minVal, minNeighborVal, minVal, minNeighborVal...
  // because minVal is the smallest possible value in the grid, 
  // so any sequence starting with [minVal, minNeighborVal, minVal] 
  // is better than [minVal, minNeighborVal, something_else_larger].
  let v1 = grid[currentR][currentC];
  let v2 = grid[nextR][nextC];

  for (let i = 1; i < k; i++) {
    if (i % 2 === 1) {
      result.push(v2);
    } else {
      result.push(v1);
    }
  }

  return result;
}
```

